@Node WhatIs? "What is Boink?"

 Since the 3x release of CNet, there has been support for UUCP Mail...
 The 4x series has even better support, thanks to the efforts of Ray Akey!
 
 This brings on other problems.  Since users may or may not have free run
 on the network from your system, it's possible that they could get deleted
 or decide to change their netname.  If someone on the net should happen to
 send mail to a non-existant user at your machine, the files just lay around
 in UUMail:.
 
 Boink solves this by 'bouncing' (or Boinking!) messages that arrived for
 users it doesnot know.  It remails the original sender letting him/her know
 that the person they mailed couldn't be found, keeps a log of bounced
 items so the Sysop may monitor activity. And optionally will place a copy
 of the Boinked mail in the Sysop/Postmasters mailbox.
 
 Boink works great with CNet because in v4.69 a 'hook' was added to the
 bbstext which will let you place the command line to call Boink and it
 will be executed after all mail is done processing in uumail: and items for
 unknown users are moved to uumail:unknown/
 
 Simple as that.
 
 Boink would not be possible if it were not for Bob Maple contributing the
 source to his UUBoing, which this program started out as. Thank you Bob!
 Bob's addy: bmaple@burner.com
 
 Kelly Cochran is also owed a bit of gratitude for his help in making Boink
 work nicely! Danke Kelly!
 Kelley's Addy: kcochran@best.com
 
 Also, much thanks to Ray Akey for continuing to provide us with CNet Amiga,
 without a doubt the best BBS software available for ANY platform!
 Ray's Addy: rakey@cnetbbs.net
 
 
 For more information, updates, bug reports, etc, please contact:
 DR. John M. Hoyt <amicon@amicon.net>
 WarNPeace on IRC - irc.beyondirc.net - #CNetIndependent
 
 
@EndNode


@Node InstallBoink "Using Boink"

 Using Boink is easier than ever thanks to a new BBSTEXT line added in
 CNet v4.69 (Thanks again Ray Akey!)...
 
 Line 2604 is our hook.  Whatever you have on that line will be executed
 upon mail-task's completion of handling the last item in uumail:
 
 You can also run Boink from a shell, or a CRON event if you wish
 It is a DOS executable, NOT a CNet C program.  However if CNet is not
 up at runtime, you MUST specify the SITE as an argument.
 
 Boink has the following command line template:
 
   Boink <SITE your.site> [DELETE] [LINES <number>] [HELPADDR <UUCPID>]
         [POSTMASTER <UUCPID>] [COPY]
   
 Commands in <> are required, ones in [] are not.  For instance, Boink
 REQUIRES the SITE keyword, followed by your site name, where as the LINES
 keyword is optional, BUT if you supply it, the number of lines is required
 immediately following.  Keyword explanations:
 
 SITE          Your sitename (REQUIRED if CNet is not running).
 DELETE        Delete bounced mail after returning it to the sender;
               Otherwise it STAYS in UUMail: and will be bounced AGAIN
               next time.  Recommended you ALWAYS supply this keyword.
 LINES         How many lines of the original message should Boink
               return, including headers?
 HELPADDR      The UUCP ID of the account help is available from on your
               system (This defaults to "sysop").
 POSTMASTER    The UUCP ID of the account you wish to be associated with
               POSTMASTER functions (where the local log will be mailed)
               etc... (This defaults to "sysop").
 COPY          Copy bounced mail to POSTMASTER (if POSTMAST not specified
               "sysop" will be assumed).


 Some examples:
 
   1> Boink SITE burner.com DELETE
   1> Boink SITE foo.machine DELETE LINES 15
   1> Boink DELETE
   1> Boink DELETE COPY
   
 Example 1 runs Boink (our site "burner.com"), and deletes any mail it
 bounces afterwards.
 
 Example 2 runs Boink (our site "foo.machine", deletes any mail it
 bounces afterwards, and will ONLY return a maximum of 15 lines of the
 original message.
 
 Example 3 would only work if CNet was running.
 
 Example 4 would place a copy on your local system in the SYSOP box.

 
 My BBSTEXT line 2604 reads:
 
 Miami:Boink >NIL: DELETE POSTMASTER jhoyt COPY
 
 Which calls Boink (in my Miami: assign, but you may place anywhere)
 and sets my system domain to amicon.net and after running deletes all
 items in uumail:unknown/ so they are not bounced again.
 
 
 When Boink bounces a message, it returns the following message to who it
 originaly came in for.
 
 The message is currently un-configurable:

 
  ## Returned message from MAILER-DAEMON@<your.site>
  
     Reason for return    : User <whomever> is not a user at this site.
     Possible explanations: The user could have been deleted off the BBS or
                            has changed his net-name.
                            
     If you need help contacting a user at this particular site, please send
     mail to '<HelpAddr>@<your.site>'.
     
  ## UN-SENT Message Follows ##
  

 The original message they sent is returned, or as many lines of the message
 will be returned if the LINES keyword was used (in which case Boink says
 "## Portion of UN-SENT message.."
 
 In addition, each item bounced is logged to cnet:sysdata/log/Boink
 letting you know that it returned a piece of mail to a non-existant user,
 and who it returned it to.

@EndNode
 
